<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="377" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,151,680]" pageId="5" pageNumber="377">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,308,151,176]" pageId="5" pageNumber="377">Remarks</emphasis>
. This new species is placed in the genus 
<taxonomicName box="[796,916,152,176]" class="Insecta" family="Gelechiidae" genus="Chionodes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="377" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[796,916,152,176]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="377">Chionodes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
based on the presence of the caecum on the aedeagus as defined by 
<bibRefCitation author="Hodges" box="[425,598,188,213]" pageId="5" pageNumber="377" refString="Hodges, R. W. (1999) The Moths of America North of Mexico. Fascicle 7.6. Gelechioidea Gelechiidae (Part. Gelechiinae (Part - Chionodes). The Wedge Entomological Research Foundation. Washington, DC, 339 pp." type="book" year="1999">
Hodges (
<number box="[529,590,188,212]" pageId="5" pageNumber="377" value="1999.0">1999</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
. The 
<typeStatus box="[664,762,188,213]" pageId="5" pageNumber="377">holotype</typeStatus>
and 
<typeStatus box="[821,917,189,213]" pageId="5" pageNumber="377">paratype</typeStatus>
are identical in habitus and genital structure. The 
<typeStatus box="[202,298,224,248]" pageId="5" pageNumber="377">paratype</typeStatus>
imago is illustrated because it possesses complete antennae. The 
<typeStatus box="[1042,1140,223,248]" pageId="5" pageNumber="377">holotype</typeStatus>
was selected because it is the specimen that yielded a nearly complete barcode sequence.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="377" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,151,680]" pageId="5" pageNumber="377">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,295,320]" pageId="5" pageNumber="377">Etymology.</emphasis>
The specific name of this species, 
<taxonomicName box="[753,884,296,320]" class="Insecta" family="Gelechiidae" genus="Chionodes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="377" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bustosorum">
<emphasis box="[753,884,296,320]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="377">bustosorum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, a noun in the genitive case, recognizes David Bustos, Chief of Resources at White Sands National Monument since 
<number box="[1013,1072,332,356]" pageId="5" pageNumber="377" value="2007.0">2007</number>
, and his wife, Andrea. David aggressively pursues research; his efforts contributed greatly to the immense accumulation of scientific data during his years at White Sands National Monument. Metzler knows from personal experience that David works long and crazy hours in support of the Monument. He is enthusiastic about the research on moths, to wit, he often sends emails to Metzler from home, long after Metzler is in bed. David is the recipient of the 
<collectingCountry box="[1117,1167,476,500]" name="United States of America" pageId="5" pageNumber="377">U.S.</collectingCountry>
National Park Service’s 
<number box="[151,207,512,536]" pageId="5" pageNumber="377" value="2014.0">2014</number>
Director's Trish Patterson Student Conservation Association Award for Natural Resource Management in a Small Park. His efforts would not be possible without the support and encouragement of his lovely wife Andrea. Metzler takes great pleasure in naming this moth in honor of David and Andrea Bustos.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="377" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,151,680]" pageId="5" pageNumber="377">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,499,620,645]" pageId="5" pageNumber="377">Distribution and biology.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName box="[506,765,620,644]" class="Insecta" family="Gelechiidae" genus="Chionodes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="377" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bustosorum">
<emphasis box="[506,765,620,644]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="377">Chionodes bustosorum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
occurs in White Sands National Monument, Otero County, New 
<collectingCountry box="[211,297,655,680]" name="Mexico" pageId="5" pageNumber="377">Mexico</collectingCountry>
(
<figureCitation box="[311,380,655,680]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1965,1987]" captionTargetBox="[271,1298,193,1920]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[271,1298,193,1936]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 3. Chionodes bustosorum type locality and distribution map. 3 a, type locality; 3 b, Chionodes bustosorum is known from White Sands National Monument, Otero Co., New Mexico." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/262009/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="377">
Fig. 
<number box="[364,380,656,680]" pageId="5" pageNumber="377" value="3.0">3</number>
</figureCitation>
). The immature stages and host plant are unknown.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
